summary.name: Bacteria_Antibiotic_Sensitivity
summary.dataset_description: This dataset contains information about the sensitivity of various bacteria to different antibiotics.

properties.description: The name of the bacteria species.
The sensitivity of the bacteria to Penicillin antibiotic.
The sensitivity of the bacteria to Streptomycin antibiotic.
The sensitivity of the bacteria to Neomycin antibiotic.
The Gram staining result of the bacteria, either positive or negative.
The genus of the bacteria species.

goals.question: What is the distribution of Penicillin sensitivity among the bacteria species?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the range of Penicillin sensitivity among different bacteria species.

goals.question: How does the sensitivity of bacteria to Streptomycin compare to that of Neomycin?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of Streptomycin vs Neomycin
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify any correlation between the sensitivity of bacteria to Streptomycin and Neomycin.

goals.question: What is the distribution of Streptomycin sensitivity among different Gram staining results?
goals.visualization: box plot of Streptomycin by Gram_Staining
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is any difference in the sensitivity of bacteria to Streptomycin based on their Gram staining result.

goals.question: Which genus of bacteria species is most sensitive to Neomycin?
goals.visualization: bar chart of Neomycin by Genus
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify the genus of bacteria species that is most sensitive to Neomycin.

goals.question: What is the correlation between the sensitivity of bacteria to Penicillin and Streptomycin?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of Penicillin vs Streptomycin
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify any correlation between the sensitivity of bacteria to Penicillin and Streptomycin.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.hist(data['Penicillin'], bins=10, color='blue', alpha=0.7, label='Penicillin Sensitivity')
    plt.axvline(data['Penicillin'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2, label=f"Median: {data['Penicillin'].median():.2f}")
    plt.xlabel('Penicillin Sensitivity')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of Penicillin sensitivity among the bacteria species?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    scatter = ax.scatter(data['Streptomycin'], data['Neomycin'], c=data['Gram_Staining'].astype('category').cat.codes, cmap='viridis')
    ax.set_xlabel('Streptomycin Sensitivity')
    ax.set_ylabel('Neomycin Sensitivity')
    ax.set_title('How does the sensitivity of bacteria to Streptomycin compare to that of Neomycin?', wrap=True)
    
    legend1 = ax.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(), title="Gram Staining")
    ax.add_artist(legend1)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    data.boxplot(column='Streptomycin', by='Gram_Staining', ax=ax)
    plt.title('What is the distribution of Streptomycin sensitivity among different Gram staining results?')
    plt.suptitle('')
    ax.set_xlabel('Gram Staining')
    ax.set_ylabel('Streptomycin Sensitivity')
    plt.xticks(rotation=0)
    plt.legend(title='Gram Staining', loc='upper right')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data_grouped = data.groupby('Genus')['Neomycin'].mean()
    ax = data_grouped.plot(kind='bar', color=['blue', 'orange', 'green', 'red'])
    plt.title('Which genus of bacteria species is most sensitive to Neomycin?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Genus')
    plt.ylabel('Average Neomycin Sensitivity')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(['Neomycin Sensitivity'])
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
